Help Type: topic
Topic: uri

Wiki Graph URIs

Purpose:
  Wiki Graph commands use URIs as their address format. Every Wiki Graph URI form is explicitly classified as either a scope URI or an object URI.
  This classification is part of the CLI contract; do not infer it from path length.

Archive locator:
  - Archive/object command URIs must contain a `.wikg` locator.
  - Do not pass a bare filesystem path as a command target.
    Use a Wiki Graph URI instead:
    /Users/me/book.wikg -> wikg:///Users/me/book.wikg
    ./book.wikg -> wikg://book.wikg
    C:\Users\me\book.wikg -> wikg://C:/Users/me/book.wikg
  - URI paths use `/` separators, including on Windows.
  - Absolute archive locators use `wikg:///`:
    wikg:///books/book.wikg
  - Relative archive locators use `wikg://`:
    wikg://book.wikg
    wikg://books/book.wikg
  - Home archive locators may start with `wikg://~/`; `~` is expanded only in that leading form:
    wikg://~/Downloads/book.wikg
  - The first path segment ending in `.wikg` is the archive/object boundary.

Short object URIs:
  Commands return short object URIs without local file paths:
    wikg://chapter/3/title
    wikg://chapter/3/source
    wikg://chapter/3/source#4..8
    wikg://chapter/3/summary
    wikg://chunk/12
    wikg://entity/Q8018
    wikg://triple/Q8018/discusses/Q123
    wikg://triple/Q8018/_/Q123

Located object URIs:
  Add an archive locator before the object path when passing a URI to a command:
    wikg:///books/book.wikg/chapter/3
    wikg:///books/book.wikg/chapter/3/source#4..8
    wikg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018
  Returned short URIs are archive-relative handles, not complete command targets. Prepend the archive locator before passing them back to object commands.
  Located readable object URIs can omit the `get` verb:
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018
  Scope URIs can omit list/search verbs:
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg/entity
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg/entity --query "keyword"

URI kind contract:
  Scope URIs enumerate objects by default. With `--query <query>`, they search within that scope.
    wikg://book.wikg
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/chunk
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/entity
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/triple
    wikg://book.wikg/chunk
    wikg://book.wikg/entity
    wikg://book.wikg/triple
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/discusses
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/_/Q123
  Object URIs read one object by default.
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/title
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/state
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/source
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/source#4..8
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/summary
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/summary#4..8
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/chunk/12
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/entity/Q8018
    wikg://book.wikg/chapter/3/triple/Q8018/discusses/Q123
    wikg://book.wikg/chunk/12
    wikg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018
    wikg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018/wikipage
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/discusses/Q123

Triple pattern lenses:
  Use `_` as an any-value placeholder for subject, predicate, or object:
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/_/Q123
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/_/_/Q123
  Trailing placeholders may be omitted:
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018
    wikg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/discusses
  Any triple URI with `_` or omitted trailing subject/predicate/object parts is a scope URI.
  A complete triple URI with concrete subject, predicate, and object is an object URI.

Object command examples:
  Search an absolute local archive:
    wikigraph wikg:///Users/me/book.wikg/entity --query "keyword"
  Open an object inside an absolute local archive:
    wikigraph wikg:///Users/me/book.wikg/entity/Q8018
  Open mapped Wikipedia pages for an entity:
    wikigraph wikg:///Users/me/book.wikg/entity/Q8018/wikipage

Archive command examples:
  Create or inspect an archive:
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg create ./book.md
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg/chapter
    wikigraph wikg://book.wikg/chapter/tree

Job URIs:
  Queue jobs use the `wikg://local/job/` scheme and do not contain `.wikg` locators:
    wikigraph wikg://local/job list
    wikigraph wikg://local/job/<job-id> get --json
    wikigraph wikg://local/job/<job-id> watch --jsonl

Scopes:
  - `wikg:///book.wikg` addresses the whole archive.
  - `wikg:///book.wikg/` is the same archive target; a trailing slash does not create a separate object.
  - `wikg:///book.wikg/chapter/3` scopes enumeration and search to chapter 3.
  - `wikg:///book.wikg/entity` searches or lists archive-wide entities.
  - `wikg:///book.wikg/chapter/3/entity` searches or lists entities scoped to chapter 3 only.
  - `wikg://chapter/3/entity/Q8018` is the entity object whose evidence must appear in chapter 3.

Object boundaries:
  - `chapter/<id>` is a scope, not an object.
  - `chapter/<id>/title` is the searchable chapter title object.
  - `source` and `summary` are readable text objects; they are not list scopes.
  - `source` is the evidence endpoint. `evidence` is not available for source or chapter scope URIs.
  - `summary`, `chunk`, `entity`, and `triple` can return source-backed evidence.

Retrieval strategy:
  Read `wikigraph help retrieval` before choosing scope, lens, pagination, or output format flags.
